ites, 8\u00d7 DVD+RW writes,<br />24\u00d7 CD read, 24\u00d7 CD-R and CD-RW recording SuperDrive<br /><span style=\"color:#969696\">''No optical drive on Server model''</span>\n|-\n! Connectivity\n|colspan=3|Built-in [[IEEE 802.11g-2003|Wi-Fi 3]] (802.11b/g)<br />[[Gigabit]] [[Ethernet]]<br />Bluetooth 2.0+EDR\nIR Receiver\n|Built-in [[IEEE 802.11n-2009|Wi-Fi 4]] (802.11a/b/g/draft-n)<br />Gigabit Ethernet<br />Bluetooth 2.1+EDR\nIR Receiver\n|Built-in Wi-Fi 4 (802.11a/b/g/n)<br />Gigabit Ethernet<br />Bluetooth 2.1+EDR\nIR Receiver\n|-\n! Peripherals\n|colspan=3 | 4x [[USB]] 2.0<br />1x [[IEEE 1394|Firewire 400]]<br />Built-in mono speaker<br />Audio-out mini-jack<br />Audio line-in/digital audio input\n|colspan=2 | 5x [[USB 2.0]]<br />1x [[FireWire 800|Firewire 800]]<br />Built-in mono speaker<br />Audio-out [[Phone connector (audio)|mini-jack]]<br />Audio line-in/digital audio input\n\n|-\n! Video out\n|colspan=3 | [[Digital Video Interface|DVI]]\n|colspan=2 | [[Mini-DVI]] and [[Mini DisplayPort]]\n|-\n! Latest release operating system <!-- NOTE: the OS has changed its name, but do not edit old naming convention to fit newer ones! -->\n|colspan=2|[[Mac OS X Snow Leopard|Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard]]\n|[[Mac OS X Lion|Mac OS X 10.7 Lion]] if 2 GB RAM installed, otherwise [[Mac OS X Snow Leopard|Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everymac.com/systems/apple/mac_mini/specs/mac-mini-core-2-duo-1.83-specs.html|title=Mac mini \"Core 2 Duo\" 1.83 Specs (Mid-2007, MB138LL/A, Macmini2,1, A1176, 2108): EveryMac.com|first=Kyle Media|last=LLC|website=www.everymac.com|accessdate=November 3, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107112935/https://everymac.com/systems/apple/mac_mini/specs/mac-mini-core-2-duo-1.83-specs.html|archivedate=November 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[OS X El Capitan|OS X 10.11 El Capitan]] if 2 GB RAM installed, otherwise [[Mac OS X Snow Leopard|Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard]]\n|[[OS X El Capitan|OS X 10.11 El Capitan]]\n|-\n! Weight\n|colspan=5|{{convert|2.9|lb|kg}}\n|-\n! Dimensions\n|colspan=5|{{convert|2.0|in|mm}} H \u00d7 {{convert|6.5|in|mm}} W \u00d7 {{convert|6.5|in|mm}} D\n|}\n\n==3rd generation (Unibody)==\n[[File:2010 Mac Mini Ports.jpg|thumb|350px|Back panel of a mid-2010 4,1 model unibody Mac mini. From left to right, first row: power button, AC power supply plug, Gigabit Ethernet, Firewire 800, HDMI, Mini-DisplayPort, 4 USB 2.0 ports, SDXC card slot. Second row: ventilation holes, audio in, audio out]]\n[[File:Mac mini mid2010 front.jpg|250px|thumbnail|right|Mac mini 2010 front view of optical drive]]\n\nOn June 15, 2010, Apple introduced the third generation Mac mini with a thinner [[monocoque|unibody]] aluminum case. It also included an internal [[power supply]] and an [[SD card]] slot.<ref name=\"unibodyoriginaldevelopment\">{{Citation |title=Designed to put more power in less space. |publisher=Apple Inc. |url=https://www.apple.com/macmini/design.html |accessdate=June 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627051656/http://www.apple.com/macmini/design.html |archivedate=June 27, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> An [[HDMI]] port, which Apple describes as being HDMI 1.4 compliant, replaces the [[Mini-DVI]] port as one of the main video connection methods.\n\nAn update announced on July 20, 2011 added a [[Thunderbolt (interface)|Thunderbolt]] port, dual-core Intel [[Core i5]] and quad-core [[Core i7|i7]] processors, support for up to 16&nbsp;GB of memory, [[Bluetooth]] 4.0, and either Intel [[HD Graphics 3000]] integrated graphics or AMD [[Comparison of AMD graphics processing units#Radeon HD 6xxxM Series|Radeon HD 6630M]] dedicated graphics. The revision also removed the internal CD/DVD optical drive from all versions. The server model was upgraded to a quad-core [[Core i7]] processor.\n\nApple updated the line on October 23, 2012 with [[Ivy Bridge (microarchitecture)|Ivy Bridge]] processors, [[USB 3.0]], and upgraded graphics.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2012/10/23/3542576/apple-announces-updated-mac-mini-starting-at-599 Apple announces updated Mac mini starting at $599]. ''The Verge''. 23 October 2012.</ref> On October 16, 2014 the line was updated with [[Haswell (microarchitecture)|Haswell]] processors, improved graphics, [[802.11ac]] Wi-Fi, and [[Thunderbolt]] 2. The Firewire 800 port was replaced with a second Thunderbolt port. The price of the base-model was lowered by $100. The only change to the body was the removal of the two holes used to open the case, as the memory was no longer upgradable because it was soldered to the logic board. Since the integrated graphics processor does not have its own dedicated memory, the system shares some of the main system memory with it.<ref>[http://support.apple.com/en-us/HT203091 Mac mini (Late 2014): Memory specifications] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210023306/http://support.apple.com/en-us/HT203091 |date=February 10, 2015 }} Retrieved February 9, 2015</ref> [[4K resolution|4K]] video output via HDMI was added.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT202856 | title=Use 4K displays and Ultra HD TVs with your Mac | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905222431/https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT202856 | archivedate=September 5, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Structure===\nThere is a removable panel on the bottom of the chassis enabling the user to upgrade the [[RAM]]. While opening the case does not actually void the warranty, anything broken while the case is open is not covered.<ref name=\"warranty\">{{Citation |title=Mac mini Late 2009 User Guide |year=2009 |page=60 |publisher=Apple Inc. |quote=If you open your Mac mini or install items, you risk damaging your equipment, and such damage isn\u2019t covered by the limited warranty on your Mac mini. |url=http://manuals.info.apple.com/en_US/Mac_mini_Late2009_UG.pdf |accessdate=June 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331212054/http://manuals.info.apple.com/en_US/Mac_mini_Late2009_UG.pdf |archivedate=March 31, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe 2011 revision removes the [[Kensington Security Slot]],<ref>{{Citation |last=Frakes |first=Dan |title=Hands on with the new Mac mini |date=June 15, 2010 |publisher=[[Mac Publishing]] |url=http://www.macworld.com/article/152061/2010/06/macmini2010handson.html |accessdate=June 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618054550/http://www.macworld.com/article/152061/2010/06/macmini2010handson.html |archivedate=June 18, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as the optical drive, leaving internal space for a second internal hard drive or SSD, which can be ordered from Apple, or as an upgrade kit from third party suppliers.\n\n===Performance===\nMac mini models released in late 2014 used dual-core processors, which perform worse in multi-threaded workloads compared to the quad-core processors from the 2012 model. Meanwhile, single-threaded workload performance increased.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.primatelabs.com/blog/2014/10/estimating-mac-mini-performance/ | title=Estimating Mac mini Performance | publisher=Primate Labs | date=October 19, 2014 | accessdate=October 19, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021192542/http://www.primatelabs.com/blog/2014/10/estimating-mac-mini-performance/ | archivedate=October 21, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Comparing the high ends of both releases, the 2012 model used a 4-core, 8-thread Intel Core [http://ark.intel.com/products/64891/Intel-Core-i7-3720QM-Processor-6M-Cache-up-to-3_60-GHz i7-3720QM], whereas the 2014 model used a 2-core, 4-thread Intel Core [http://ark.intel.com/products/83506/Intel-Core-i7-4578U-Processor-4M-Cache-up-to-3_50-GHz i7-4578U].\n\nThe 2014 model featured Intel Iris graphics (GT3), which greatly outperforms the Intel HD Graphics 4000 (GT2) in the previous models.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://anandtech.com/show/6926/intel-iris-iris-pro-graphics-haswell-gt3gt3e-gets-a-brand | title=Intel Iris & Iris Pro Graphics: Haswell GT3/GT3e Gets a Brand | publisher=AnandTech | date=May 1, 2013 | accessdate=October 19, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022010613/http://www.anandtech.com/show/6926/intel-iris-iris-pro-graphics-haswell-gt3gt3e-gets-a-brand | archivedate=October 22, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The late 2014 CPUs were also more energy-efficient: their maximal thermal design power (TDP) was 62% lower than that of the 2012 models.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cpu-world.com/Compare/277/Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-3720QM_(PGA)_vs_Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-4578U.html | title=Intel Core i7-3720QM (PGA) vs i7-4578U | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212162451/http://www.cpu-world.com/Compare/277/Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-3720QM_(PGA)_vs_Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-4578U.html | archivedate=February 12, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cpu-world.com/Compare/263/Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-3720QM_(BGA)_vs_Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-4578U.html | title=Intel Core i7-3720QM (BGA) vs i7-4578U | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212091857/http://www.cpu-world.com/Compare/263/Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-3720QM_(BGA)_vs_Intel_Core_i7_Mobile_i7-4578U.html | archivedate=February 12, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nIn general, the Mac mini has been praised as a relatively affordable computer with a solid range of features. Reviews noted it is possible to purchase small computers at the same price with faster processors, better graphics card, more memory, and more storage.<ref>{{Citation |last=Frakes |first=Dan |title=Mac mini (Late 2009) Review |publisher=[[Mac Publishing]] |date=November 3, 2009 |url=http://www.macworld.com/article/143611/2009/11/macminilate2009.html |accessdate=June 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616083133/http://www.macworld.com/article/143611/2009/11/macminilate2009.html |archivedate=June 16, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The small size has made the Mac mini particularly popular as a home theater solution. In addition, its size and reliability has helped keep resale values high.<ref>{{Citation |title=The market for used Mac minis |date=August 2013 |work=Macminicolo.net |url=http://blog.macminicolo.net/post/57713423680/the-market-for-used-mac-minis |accessdate=2017-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202044308/http://blog.macminicolo.net/post/57713423680/the-market-for-used-mac-minis |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Specifications===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| style=\"background:#FFDDDD;\"|\n| <abbr title=\"Mac products that were discontinued between 5 and 7 years ago but still support the latest macOS software release. Hardware support provided only through Apple Service Providers in the United States and Turkey.\">Vintage</abbr>\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\"|\n| Discontinued\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n<!-- 2 or 3 columns per release -->\n|-\n!style=\"width:10%\"| Component\n!colspan=2| [[Intel Core 2 Duo]]\n!colspan=9| Intel [[Core i7#Core i5 2|Core i5]] & [[Core i7#Core i7 2|i7]]\n|-\n!style=width:8%\"|Model\n!colspan=2 style=\"background:#FFDDDD;width:20%\"|{{nowrap|Mid 2010}}<ref name=\"Mid 2010\">{{Citation |title=Mac mini (Mid 2010) \u2013 Technical Specifications |date=June 15, 2010 |publisher=Apple Inc. |url=http://support.apple.com/kb/SP585 |accessdate=June 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622043430/http://support.apple.com/kb/SP585 |archivedate=June 22, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Mid 2010 server\">{{Citation |title=Mac mini Server (Mid 2010) \u2013 Technical Specifications |date=June 15, 2010 |publisher=Apple Inc. |url=http://support.apple.com/kb/SP586 |accessdate=June 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831222732/http://support.apple.